Wait — the test expects the *first* participant to get 3334, but my code gives the remainder to the *last*. The spec says "first N participants get one extra cent; N = remainder." Let me look at how `CalculateEqualSplit` handles this — it uses `i < remainder` to give extra cents to the first participants. I should follow the same pattern for Shares.

But wait — the Shares calculation is different from Equal. In Equal, each participant gets `total / count` with `total % count` remainder distributed to the first N. In Shares, each participant gets `(shares * total) / totalShares` — the truncation happens per-participant, not globally. The "last participant gets remainder" approach is actually the correct general approach because it guarantees the sum invariant regardless of how the truncation distributes.

But the test expects the *first* participant to get 3334. Let me re-read the test assertion... The test says "first participant in request order receives the 1-cent remainder." So I need to distribute the remainder to the first participants, not the last.

